(128, 1, '2017-03-16 14:07:46', '2017-03-16 14:07:46', 'Russian Railroads is a fairly complex worker placement game. It maxes out to 4 players but it can also be a tight 2-3 player match. In this game, you play the roles of Russian moguls planning on building locomotive routes on the 3 longest railroads in the USSR. As far as worker placement games go, this could be hard to teach. However, if you play with eager people who have already played relatively light worker placement games, the mechanics may not be that daunting. The turn is really simple: Place a worker, do the action, pass the turn to the next player. It''s the repercussions of the actions that make the game a bit complex. You have trains and tracks and factories and --- you get the drift. Also, the scoring system can be quite a handful, but nothing you can''t manage if you''ve played other mid-weight games before.\r\n\r\n<strong>Fun Factor</strong>\r\n\r\nThis is one of those titles where the tone will largely depend on the personalities around the table. Sure the concept may sound dry and unappealing: after all, it''s a game about trains and working out efficient strategies, but there''s more to it than that. If everyone''s fairly competitive and are OK with the "tacked-on" theme, the game can actually be fun. In some cases though, playing with people who have short attention spans and are not enticed by the mechanics can be a problem. The experience will be a dreary 90-minute slog.\r\n\r\n<strong>Component Quality</strong>\r\n\r\nI have to say, this is not as flashy as games like Ticket to Ride or Five Tribes as the game components are fairly average. You have the standard cardboard cut-outs and some meeples here and there. What it lacks in aesthetics are made up for by the meaty gameplay it provides. Don''t get me wrong though, the components aren''t low-quality, they just don''t stack up that much with the production values of higher-end games.\r\n\r\n<strong>Replayability</strong>\r\n\r\nNow this is where I tip my hat to Russian Railroads. I''ve played it maybe 6x at the time of this writing and I''ve yet to crack the "most efficient" strategy. The beauty of the game is that there are a lot of options to choose from. You can go focus on just 2 railroads and maximize their benefits, or be a jack of all trades and focus on both railroads and factories. At the very least, the replay value ramps up once you finish a game or two with players who also love the game. It''s not a play another game right after the first one kind-of-thing but it''s more of a let''s plan another game session of this because I want to score better.', 'Russian Railroads', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '117-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-03-16 14:07:46', '2017-03-16 14:07:46', '', 117, 'http://localhost/meepler/?p=128', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(129, 1, '2017-03-16 14:10:52', '2017-03-16 14:10:52', '<strong>Complexity</strong>\r\n\r\nRussian Railroads is a fairly complex worker placement game. It maxes out to 4 players but it can also be a tight 2-3 player match. In this game, you play the roles of Russian moguls planning on building locomotive routes on the 3 longest railroads in the USSR. As far as worker placement games go, this could be hard to teach. However, if you play with eager people who have already played relatively light worker placement games, the mechanics may not be that daunting. The turn is really simple: Place a worker, do the action, pass the turn to the next player. It''s the repercussions of the actions that make the game a bit complex. You have trains and tracks and factories and --- you get the drift. Also, the scoring system can be quite a handful, but nothing you can''t manage if you''ve played other mid-weight games before.\r\n\r\n<strong>Fun Factor</strong>\r\n\r\nThis is one of those titles where the tone will largely depend on the personalities around the table. Sure the concept may sound dry and unappealing: after all, it''s a game about trains and working out efficient strategies, but there''s more to it than that. If everyone''s fairly competitive and are OK with the "tacked-on" theme, the game can actually be fun. In some cases though, playing with people who have short attention spans and are not enticed by the mechanics can be a problem. The experience will be a dreary 90-minute slog.\r\n\r\n<strong>Component Quality</strong>\r\n\r\nI have to say, this is not as flashy as games like Ticket to Ride or Five Tribes as the game components are fairly average. You have the standard cardboard cut-outs and some meeples here and there. What it lacks in aesthetics are made up for by the meaty gameplay it provides. Don''t get me wrong though, the components aren''t low-quality, they just don''t stack up that much with the production values of higher-end games.\r\n\r\n<strong>Replayability</strong>\r\n\r\nNow this is where I tip my hat to Russian Railroads. I''ve played it maybe 6x at the time of this writing and I''ve yet to crack the "most efficient" strategy. The beauty of the game is that there are a lot of options to choose from. You can go focus on just 2 railroads and maximize their benefits, or be a jack of all trades and focus on both railroads and factories. At the very least, the replay value ramps up once you finish a game or two with players who also love the game. It''s not a play another game right after the first one kind-of-thing but it''s more of a let''s plan another game session of this because I want to score better.', 'Russian Railroads', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '117-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-03-16 14:10:52', '2017-03-16 14:10:52', '', 117, 'http://localhost/meepler/?p=129', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
